<paper id="1938714998"><title>Hierarchical Model-Based Motion Estimation</title><year>1992</year><authors><author org="David Sarnoff Research Center," id="2154907102">James R. Bergen</author><author org="David Sarnoff Research Center," id="2709234686">P. Anandan</author><author org="David Sarnoff Research Center," id="2130597182">Keith J. Hanna</author><author org="David Sarnoff Research Center," id="1990987094">Rajesh Hingorani</author></authors><n_citation>1206</n_citation><doc_type>Conference</doc_type><references><reference>1530066183</reference><reference>1578285471</reference><reference>1991518198</reference><reference>2025510965</reference><reference>2043003144</reference><reference>2081171933</reference><reference>2102956030</reference><reference>2118877769</reference><reference>2141228894</reference><reference>2168262846</reference><reference>2168564612</reference><reference>2940879937</reference></references><venue id="1124077590" type="C">European Conference on Computer Vision</venue><doi>10.1007/3-540-55426-2_27</doi><keywords><keyword weight="0.57014">Affine transformation</keyword><keyword weight="0.4626">Computer vision</keyword><keyword weight="0.43157">Computer science</keyword><keyword weight="0.43451">Flow (psychology)</keyword><keyword weight="0.52675">Rigid body</keyword><keyword weight="0.44326">Planar</keyword><keyword weight="0.0">Artificial intelligence</keyword><keyword weight="0.68702">Motion estimation</keyword><keyword weight="0.54406">Hierarchical database model</keyword><keyword weight="0.64435">Optical flow</keyword><keyword weight="0.52167">Computation</keyword></keywords><publisher>Springer, Berlin, Heidelberg</publisher><abstract>This paper describes a hierarchical estimation framework for the computation of diverse representations of motion information. The key features of the resulting framework (or family of algorithms) are a global model that constrains the overall structure of the motion estimated, a local model that is used in the estimation process, and a coarse-fine refinement strategy. Four specific motion models: affine flow, planar surface flow, rigid body motion, and general optical flow, are described along with their application to specific examples.</abstract></paper>